This paper focuses on improving the cross-domain robustness of object detection, which is a common problem in computer vision. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also proposes a domain adaptation approach based on adversarial training, which involves learning a domain classifier, indicating that it may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of H-divergence theory, which is a statistical measure of the difference between two probability distributions, suggesting that it could be categorized as cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also evaluates its approach on multiple datasets, including Cityscapes and KITTI, which are commonly used in computer vision research, indicating that it may belong to cs.MM (Multimedia) as well. Finally, the paper deals with object detection, which is a subfield of robotics, suggesting that it could also be categorized as cs.RO (Robotics).
